3047. Largest Area of Square Inside Two Rectangles
ðŸ”¹ Core Idea

A square can fit inside the intersection of two rectangles.

So for every pair of rectangles:

Find their overlapping region

From that region, the largest possible square side is:

side = min(overlap_width, overlap_height)


We need the maximum sideÂ² over all pairs.

ðŸ”¹ Rectangle Intersection

For rectangles i and j:

left   = max(x1_i, x1_j)
right  = min(x2_i, x2_j)
bottom = max(y1_i, y1_j)
top    = min(y2_i, y2_j)

width  = right - left
height = top - bottom


If width <= 0 or height <= 0 â†’ no intersection.

ðŸ”¹ Square Inside Intersection

A square must fit completely inside the overlap:

max_square_side = min(width, height)
area = side * side

ðŸ”¹ Algorithm
maxSide = 0
for i = 0..n-1:
  for j = i+1..n-1:
      compute overlap width & height
      side = min(width, height)
      maxSide = max(maxSide, side)

return maxSide * maxSide

ðŸ”¹ Time & Space
Metric	Value
Time	O(nÂ²)
Space	O(1)

n â‰¤ 1000, so nÂ² = 10â¶ â†’ totally fine.

ðŸ”¹ Key Observations (Interview Points)

We donâ€™t need all rectangles, only pairs

Bigger intersection â‡’ potentially bigger square

Square is limited by shorter side of the overlap

Intersection logic = max of starts, min of ends

ðŸ”¹ Common Mistakes

âŒ Forgetting negative width/height
âŒ Taking max(width, height) instead of min
âŒ Not using long long for area
âŒ Off-by-one in intersection boundaries

ðŸ”¹ Mental Formula

Two rectangles â†’ find overlap â†’ smallest side â†’ square â†’ maximize
